  "prompt": "What are the causes for receding gums?",
  "response": "Receding gums, also known as gingival recession, is a common dental problem where the gum tissue pulls back, exposing more of the tooth or tooth root. This can lead to sensitivity, increased risk of cavities, and even tooth loss if left untreated.  Here are some of the most common causes:\n\n**1. Periodontal Disease (Gum Disease):**\n\n*   **Bacterial Infection:** This is the most frequent cause. Bacteria in plaque and tartar build up and inflame the gums, eventually destroying the gum tissue and bone that hold the teeth in place.  Gingivitis (early gum disease) can progress to periodontitis (advanced gum disease) if left untreated.\n\n**2. Aggressive Toothbrushing:**\n\n*   **Hard Bristles and Excessive Force:**  Brushing too hard or using a toothbrush with hard bristles can erode the gum tissue over time. A soft-bristled brush and gentle circular motions are recommended.\n\n**3. Genetics:**\n\n*   **Predisposition:** Some people are simply genetically predisposed to gum recession.  They may have thinner gum tissue that is more susceptible to damage.\n\n**4. Poor Oral Hygiene:**\n\n*   **Plaque and Tartar Build-up:**  Inadequate brushing and flossing allow plaque and tartar to accumulate along the gum line, contributing to inflammation and eventual recession, even without progressing to full-blown periodontitis.\n\n**5. Tobacco Use:**\n\n*   **Reduced Blood Flow:** Smoking and chewing tobacco reduce blood flow to the gums, hindering their ability to heal and making them more vulnerable to infection and recession.\n\n**6. Hormonal Changes:**\n\n*   **Fluctuations:** Hormonal fluctuations, particularly in women during puberty, pregnancy, and menopause, can make gums more sensitive and susceptible to inflammation and recession.\n\n**7. Bruxism (Teeth Grinding/Clenching):**\n\n*   **Excessive Force:** Grinding or clenching your teeth (often during sleep) puts excessive force on the teeth and surrounding tissues, contributing to gum recession.\n\n**8. Misaligned Teeth or a Crooked Bite:**\n\n*   **Uneven Pressure:**  Teeth that are not properly aligned can put uneven pressure on the gums and bone, leading to recession in certain areas.\n\n**9. Lip or Tongue Frenum Pull:**\n\n*   **Frenum Attachment:**  A frenum is a small fold of tissue that connects the lip or tongue to the gums.  If the frenum is attached too close to the gum line, it can pull on the gums and cause recession.\n\n**10. Trauma to the Gums:**\n\n*   **Injury:**  Injury to the gums, such as from dental procedures or accidents, can damage the tissue and lead to recession.\n\n**11. Piercings:**\n\n*   **Oral Piercings:**  Lip or tongue piercings can irritate the gums and wear away at the gum line.\n\n**12. Orthodontic Treatment:**\n\n*   **Tooth Movement:** While orthodontic treatment aims to improve oral health, in some cases, it can contribute to gum recession, especially if teeth are moved too quickly or if the gums are already thin.\n\n**13. Certain Medical Conditions:**\n\n*   **Rarely:** Some medical conditions can indirectly contribute to gum recession.\n\n**Important Note:**\n\nIt's crucial to consult a dentist if you notice any signs of receding gums, such as increased tooth sensitivity, longer-appearing teeth, or visible tooth roots. Early detection and treatment can help prevent further damage and maintain your oral health.\n",
